      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at some paperwork for a shipment from ningbo and i'm a bit confused. can u explain the main difference between CIF and FOB under incoterms 2020? specifically who handles the insurance and when does the risk actually transfer to us?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main difference between CIF and FOB lies in who manages the shipment's risks and costs. Under FOB (Free On Board), the buyer takes on the risk and cost once the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the origin port. In contrast, CIF (Cost, Insurance, and Freight) means the seller is responsible for arranging and paying for the main carriage and insurance up to the named port of destination. Therefore, with CIF, the risk transfers to you usually when the goods are loaded onto the ship, but the seller handles the primary insurance arrangement.",
      "source": "target",
